  "prompt": "What has replaced CGI (common gateway interface) in today's web?",
  "response": "Several modern technologies have replaced the Common Gateway Interface (CGI) for web development, offering enhanced performance, scalability, and ease of use. Some of the most notable replacements include:\n\n1. **Server-Side Frameworks**: Frameworks such as Node.js, Django, Ruby on Rails, and ASP.NET allow for more efficient handling of web requests, with built-in features that streamline development and improve performance.\n\n2. **Web Servers with Modular Architectures**: Modern web servers like Nginx and Apache offer robust modules and configurations that can handle dynamic content without needing CGI.\n\n3. **APIs and Microservices**: RESTful APIs, GraphQL, and other microservices architectures facilitate the creation of scalable, decoupled web applications by enabling client-server interactions through lightweight, standardized interfaces.\n\n4. **Serverless Computing**: Platforms such as AWS Lambda, Google Cloud Functions, and Azure Functions enable developers to run backend code in response to events without managing server infrastructure, providing automatic scaling and pay-per-use models.\n\n5. **Containers and Orchestration Tools**: Docker and Kubernetes allow for the deployment and management of web applications in containers, providing greater flexibility, scalability, and ease of updating and maintaining applications.\n\nOverall, these modern technologies offer sophisticated features and improved efficiency compared to CGI, making them more suitable for today's demanding web applications.",
